1
00:00:00,875 --> 00:00:09,346
So really just to revise the principles of meditation and some of the pitfalls and all that.

2
00:00:15,314 --> 00:00:20,321
It's always good to go back to the Buddha himself, you know, his own personal experience.

3
00:00:21,521 --> 00:00:28,131
And to remember that right until the very end of his search for an answer that was

4
00:00:29,443 --> 00:00:39,218
you know, deep within his own heart this business around suffering really he didn't he couldn't find the answer to it and he was pretty stuck.

5
00:00:39,317 --> 00:00:50,412
By the time he came to leave his companions it must have looked to him it must have looked to him that there really wasn't an answer.

6
00:00:51,134 --> 00:00:58,725
Because everything that the society at that time had to offer, had been offered and he'd done it to the best of his abilities and he got nowhere.

7
00:01:00,375 --> 00:01:27,936
It was only when he sat there and was refreshed with a bowl of rice pudding everybody knows the power of rice pudding that he just remembered this occasion in childhood when he was watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony and there was something about that watching which awoke in him another possibility

8
00:01:28,962 --> 00:01:42,296
So his earlier practice had been to do with what we call the jhanas, these absorptions which is something you can manipulate, something you can do with your mind you can make it feel, you can make your heart feel blissful.

9
00:01:43,254 --> 00:01:46,680
So it's an actual doing, it's an actual something you can achieve.

10
00:01:48,361 --> 00:02:00,278
Just like we can achieve through the repetition of phrases and natural, just repetition of phrases and scenes and just talking to ourselves and we can get into a nice deep depression.

11
00:02:01,980 --> 00:02:06,406
So in the same way you can talk to yourself and lift yourself up.

12
00:02:06,427 --> 00:02:11,152
And then there was that business of self-mortification where the

13
00:02:11,706 --> 00:02:13,588
error was seen to be in the body itself.

14
00:02:14,150 --> 00:02:22,639
So, it's the body that has pleasure and therefore one tries to subdue that and in doing so one attains a certain type of peace.

15
00:02:24,001 --> 00:02:33,191
But the problem was that that just led him towards starvation and death which didn't present itself as the most brilliant answer to his problem.

16
00:02:34,492 --> 00:02:40,278
So, it was only when he went back to this childhood experience

17
00:02:42,081 --> 00:02:53,211
And what is it about the child, especially before the age of seven, that is different from an adult's way of seeing the world?

18
00:02:53,913 --> 00:02:57,915
And it's that it isn't yet confused by concepts and experiences.

19
00:02:59,277 --> 00:03:05,864
So that intelligence is still, shall we say, in a very pure state of just receiving, just receiving.

20
00:03:07,205 --> 00:03:10,687
And the ability to

21
00:03:11,241 --> 00:03:17,349
No, receive without criticism, receive without judgment, receive without past experience.

22
00:03:20,213 --> 00:03:22,657
And then of course it has to make sense of it.

23
00:03:22,676 --> 00:03:25,921
And adults tell it how to make sense of it and that's the end of that.

24
00:03:29,186 --> 00:03:36,955
So it's a case of really rediscovering that original mind that we had then, the original intelligence we had then.

25
00:03:37,516 --> 00:03:38,277
That's all it is.

26
00:03:39,187 --> 00:03:44,111
And to do that, we keep pulling ourselves out of the mind.

27
00:03:44,151 --> 00:03:49,157
We keep getting out of our own mind, exiting from our own emotions.

28
00:03:51,659 --> 00:04:00,949
We find that position within ourselves where we're actually watching, feeling, experiencing an emotion, which is very different from being it, isn't it?

29
00:04:01,330 --> 00:04:05,734
Very different from being angry to feeling the anger as something within you.

30
00:04:07,216 --> 00:04:16,827
And when the body comes with its tickles and its pains to actually see it as objective and to investigate it just as a sensation.

31
00:04:16,987 --> 00:04:18,089
What is a sensation?

32
00:04:21,593 --> 00:04:26,240
What is an itch before you call it an itch?

33
00:04:26,259 --> 00:04:28,202
As soon as you say it's an itch you've got to scratch it.

34
00:04:29,625 --> 00:04:36,192
But if you go before you call it an itch see there isn't the impulse to scratch really.

35
00:04:36,375 --> 00:04:40,062
All it is is little fiery little sensations.

36
00:04:41,103 --> 00:04:41,944
The same with eating.

37
00:04:42,865 --> 00:04:47,632
As soon as you say I'm hungry or I am hungry or there is hunger, there's the impulsion to eat.

38
00:04:49,035 --> 00:04:55,625
If you go below that, just the sensations, they're just tickly sensations in the stomach.

39
00:04:55,644 --> 00:05:04,358
So there's something happening in our mentation which is losing, shall we say, that initial direct contact

40
00:05:05,906 --> 00:05:12,435
it immediately flips into conceptual thinking, historical thinking, conditioned thinking.

41
00:05:12,536 --> 00:05:14,999
That's what we mean by this conditioning.

42
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:20,206
It's something we build up within ourselves.

43
00:05:20,225 --> 00:05:27,355
So what we're trying to do in the meditation is to allow the mind to express all this, allow the heart to express all its emotional states.

44
00:05:28,096 --> 00:05:31,019
Let the body be uncomfortable, comfortable, doesn't matter.

45
00:05:31,877 --> 00:05:47,677
and to discover that access point where we're no longer involved in it, we're no longer caught up in it and from that point we can observe, we can feel, we can experience and in so doing we can see how we create the world that we live in.

46
00:05:53,826 --> 00:05:58,932
So, the whole of our practice is keep on accessing that position.

47
00:05:59,569 --> 00:06:01,752
And that position has to become clear to us.

48
00:06:02,374 --> 00:06:06,199
It has to become clear to us by direct personal experience.

49
00:06:07,821 --> 00:06:13,088
Nobody can describe it to you, can tell you what it is, to a point.

50
00:06:14,129 --> 00:06:24,041
All these words that I'm saying now would be meaningless unless you've done some meditation and actually tried to experience this business of distancing from what was inside you.

51
00:06:28,983 --> 00:06:55,192
so just as we don't have any problem with knowing that this room is outside my body we've made that objective we've made that an object we can create a relationship to it and say it's my room in which case I get worried and anxious about it but I'm much easier with just saying it is a room it belongs to somebody else and I can do what I want inside it and not get too worried

52
00:06:55,696 --> 00:07:03,144
So that business of being able to see things as not connected to me in that way of being mine.

53
00:07:05,547 --> 00:07:10,112
So when I go inward, you see, I have this anger, this depression, this stress.

54
00:07:10,413 --> 00:07:13,737
And on the other side I have joy, affection, love.

55
00:07:14,918 --> 00:07:24,910
As soon as I say it's mine, I'm forming a relationship with that which is going to cramp the mind and heart, you see.

56
00:07:26,560 --> 00:07:29,103
Now, in what way does it cramp it, you see?

57
00:07:29,624 --> 00:07:31,788
It cramps it because it has the service.

58
00:07:32,127 --> 00:07:34,511
It comes into the service of me.

59
00:07:35,293 --> 00:07:36,074
So, this me.

60
00:07:37,956 --> 00:07:43,463
So, when you drive yourself down to this me, what does this me want, you see?

61
00:07:43,545 --> 00:07:47,050
What do I want from the world I live in?

62
00:07:48,572 --> 00:07:51,095
So, it's as we said last night, I want to be happy.

63
00:07:52,057 --> 00:07:52,898
It's fair enough, isn't it?

64
00:07:53,699 --> 00:07:54,519
I just want to be happy.

65
00:07:55,541 --> 00:07:55,622
See?

66
00:07:56,750 --> 00:08:03,920
And unfortunately this I presumes that its happiness can be found by manipulating the world.

67
00:08:04,480 --> 00:08:10,428
I'd be happy if people served me food and drove me around a bit.

68
00:08:11,651 --> 00:08:17,600
So then I have to manipulate people to make sure that I get what I want.

69
00:08:18,380 --> 00:08:21,745
And of course if they don't service me then I want to get rid of them.

70
00:08:22,427 --> 00:08:24,850
What's the point of having people around who aren't going to service my wants?

71
00:08:26,281 --> 00:08:27,202
The same with objects.

72
00:08:27,262 --> 00:08:29,846
If I don't like an object, see, I chuck it away.

73
00:08:29,887 --> 00:08:31,949
And if I do like it, hold on to it.

74
00:08:33,513 --> 00:08:34,413
Put it under lock and key.

75
00:08:36,037 --> 00:08:36,177
See?

76
00:08:36,817 --> 00:08:40,745
So the world becomes a place of, it becomes a dangerous place.

77
00:08:40,865 --> 00:08:46,354
It becomes a place where I have to hold on to what I have in case I become unhappy.

78
00:08:47,254 --> 00:08:49,840
I have to keep away all those things that make me unhappy.

79
00:08:52,123 --> 00:08:53,065
The Scrooge.

80
00:08:54,580 --> 00:08:56,542
Yeah, go keep what makes me happy.

81
00:08:57,143 --> 00:09:12,482
So, when we are practicing meditation, we're going in, into the mind, into the body itself, into the heart itself, to actually feel what's going on there and to recognize that relationship we have.

82
00:09:13,823 --> 00:09:16,226
Like it, don't like it, want it, don't want it.

83
00:09:16,346 --> 00:09:17,188
So it starts here.

84
00:09:18,330 --> 00:09:21,774
Everything out there is just a projection of what I've decided I need.

85
00:09:23,056 --> 00:09:23,135
Hmm?

86
00:09:23,825 --> 00:09:28,229
So if I go in here and I feel loneliness, oh, see, I project it outwards.

87
00:09:28,269 --> 00:09:29,570
I've got to heal it out there.

88
00:09:30,230 --> 00:09:32,211
So I phone up a friend and say, look, I'm very lonely.

89
00:09:33,573 --> 00:09:34,134
Oh, don't worry.

90
00:09:35,595 --> 00:09:38,918
I'll come and have a pint with you.

91
00:09:38,937 --> 00:09:40,259
And you think, oh, that's healed, you see.

92
00:09:40,278 --> 00:09:41,600
You have a pint, you feel good.

93
00:09:42,380 --> 00:09:44,363
And you think, oh, that's how to cure loneliness.

94
00:09:45,443 --> 00:09:45,583
See?

95
00:09:45,764 --> 00:09:46,865
Until your friend drops dead.

96
00:09:47,966 --> 00:09:49,927
And then the loneliest comes up and says, the friend's not there.

97
00:09:50,168 --> 00:09:51,308
And you're stuck with this loneliness.

98
00:09:53,331 --> 00:09:53,410
See?

99
00:09:53,431 --> 00:09:53,510
See?

100
00:09:54,283 --> 00:09:58,988
So now all these problems we have within us can't be solved by anything outside us.

101
00:10:00,710 --> 00:10:17,384
So it's actually only through coming into contact with these problems inside us and to actually feel them and allow them to express themselves and to express themselves without any interference that we realize actually that that's the curing process.

102
00:10:17,403 --> 00:10:24,190
All they want to do is tell us how sad they are how lonely they are how upset they are how angry they are

103
00:10:24,591 --> 00:10:27,796
Once you've listened to it and felt it, they just go away.

104
00:10:28,557 --> 00:10:29,457
They just fade out.

105
00:10:29,498 --> 00:10:32,221
They exhaust themselves.

106
00:10:32,240 --> 00:10:37,927
And it's just having that patience, that willingness to receive, no matter how hard it is.

107
00:10:38,168 --> 00:10:40,630
I mean, some of the stuff's pretty awful.

108
00:10:42,832 --> 00:10:45,475
And it's just being able to be open to that.

109
00:10:45,495 --> 00:10:49,801
Now, we'll be much easier with the stuff if we don't identify with it.

110
00:10:51,102 --> 00:10:51,222
Right?

111
00:10:51,845 --> 00:10:59,519
So that's why in our meditation we try to take this position of the onlooker, the observer, the one who knows.

112
00:11:01,143 --> 00:11:09,018
And that distance, that distance from what we experience within ourselves, that's the process of detaching, of detaching.

113
00:11:11,643 --> 00:11:13,667
Now, so that that distance

114
00:11:13,967 --> 00:11:30,423
detachment doesn't become brittle doesn't become hard doesn't become in a sense another subtle way of not feeling things you have to open your heart out as it were to what's arising and that's the importance of metta

115
00:11:31,365 --> 00:11:44,726
So this looking, this onward looking has to be, it's best if it's flavoured with that attitude of wanting to heal what's there.

116
00:11:45,508 --> 00:11:49,815
And you've got to be careful here because that presumes some sort of achievement.

117
00:11:49,835 --> 00:11:58,268
But it's looking down or looking at what is happening within us in a kindly way, in a gentle way.

118
00:11:58,484 --> 00:12:00,365
And that's the process of metta, you see.

119
00:12:00,586 --> 00:12:05,692
That's why this vipassana and metta are two things that need to balance each other.

120
00:12:06,452 --> 00:12:12,941
So it's a warm, it's a warm onlooking, it's a warm investigation.

121
00:12:17,946 --> 00:12:23,852
And when you do that, you see, it undermines all those judgmental phrases that come up.

122
00:12:23,893 --> 00:12:24,953
This is terrible.

123
00:12:25,715 --> 00:12:26,395
I'm useless.

124
00:12:26,996 --> 00:12:28,018
All that sort of stuff.

125
00:12:28,927 --> 00:12:34,712
So developing that looking down upon with compassion.

126
00:12:35,313 --> 00:12:44,082
So in the Mahayana you see the Avalokitesvara, the compassionate Buddha, the one that looks down upon with compassion.

127
00:12:46,404 --> 00:12:56,115
So that's what we're trying to do within ourselves is to create, is to discover the Buddha within us and to give it that flavor of compassion towards ourselves.

128
00:12:58,592 --> 00:13:09,948
So now, once we're pretty clear about that we want to always access this position of the onlooker, the witness, the observer, that's not, remember, the most perfect state.

129
00:13:10,048 --> 00:13:17,639
It's only when the idea of me looking down, me observing, disappears too, that it's any true vipassana.

130
00:13:18,120 --> 00:13:20,482
That can't happen by an act of will.

131
00:13:21,104 --> 00:13:23,506
We can get ourselves to an onlooker by an act of will.

132
00:13:24,629 --> 00:13:26,270
You can say, right, now let's look at this.

133
00:13:26,655 --> 00:13:28,438
And immediately you pull yourself out.

134
00:13:28,698 --> 00:13:30,201
This consciousness pulls itself out.

135
00:13:31,504 --> 00:13:33,466
But it can't do that with the self.

136
00:13:34,428 --> 00:13:37,914
And that's our unfortunate situation.

137
00:13:38,394 --> 00:13:40,479
You cannot by an act of will get rid of the self.

138
00:13:41,561 --> 00:13:44,044
All you do is create another self, getting rid of the self you don't want.

139
00:13:46,008 --> 00:13:50,975
So the only way that sense of self disappears is

140
00:13:51,495 --> 00:14:00,846
by bringing that attention, and that's where this sense of concentration comes in, bringing that attention into the immediate moment.

141
00:14:00,866 --> 00:14:14,702
And when, as you draw through interest and through investigation, through concentration and effort, into the immediate moment, you see, there's no time for that reflection, for the afterthought, I'm looking.

142
00:14:15,764 --> 00:14:17,706
And those are moments of pure vipassana.

143
00:14:18,412 --> 00:14:25,381
They're happening anyway in your practice, believe it or not, but they're just so small that you probably haven't noticed.

144
00:14:25,402 --> 00:14:36,259
And it's extending those moments and waking up out of them that you realize for that point of time, for that little measure of time, there was just awareness.

145
00:14:36,278 --> 00:14:37,440
There was just the knowing.

146
00:14:40,345 --> 00:14:45,852
Now that is what we're trying to develop towards and

147
00:14:46,288 --> 00:14:51,657
our skills of meditation are about how to work with the hindrances when they come up.

148
00:14:53,038 --> 00:14:56,864
So, you know, that's a skill and that takes effort.

149
00:14:57,605 --> 00:15:03,452
So what do you do when you get these feelings of tiredness and sloth in the body and dullness in the mind, you see?

150
00:15:04,595 --> 00:15:13,748
So the first thing, of course, is to so long as you're clear that it is lethargy and dullness that it isn't that you need sleep

151
00:15:14,081 --> 00:15:16,966
So this might not be clear on such a small retreat like this.

152
00:15:18,788 --> 00:15:20,370
So give yourself the benefit of the doubt.

153
00:15:21,393 --> 00:15:23,735
But not too much.

154
00:15:23,755 --> 00:15:31,927
And so when you get these feelings of lethargy, you see, so know that they're there, you see, and just make that mental determination.

155
00:15:32,528 --> 00:15:34,291
You know, I'm not going to give in to this.

156
00:15:34,892 --> 00:15:36,794
See, just refuse to be annihilated.

157
00:15:38,356 --> 00:15:40,681
And then work with them.

158
00:15:41,020 --> 00:15:43,183
See, open your eyes to make sure that you're awake.

159
00:15:43,203 --> 00:15:43,784
Stand up.

160
00:15:43,933 --> 00:15:44,254
You see?

161
00:15:44,634 --> 00:15:45,696
Don't feel that's a failure.

162
00:15:46,518 --> 00:15:50,722
Standing meditation is perfectly equal to sitting meditation.

163
00:15:51,443 --> 00:15:56,572
You know, as you stand up thinking, oh, all these people are there, what a terrible meditator.

164
00:15:56,912 --> 00:16:04,361
Stand up, you can, you know, if it's really, really bad, before you fall over, you can leave the room and walk up and down a bit.

165
00:16:04,381 --> 00:16:06,044
And just keep yourself, keep yourself awake.

166
00:16:06,485 --> 00:16:07,667
And what is your object?

167
00:16:07,947 --> 00:16:09,990
What is it that you're investigating?

168
00:16:10,350 --> 00:16:11,292
Well, these very feelings.

169
00:16:12,384 --> 00:16:15,749
The dullness in the mind, you know, it's like porridge in the mind, in the head.

170
00:16:16,669 --> 00:16:18,753
And the feeling of the body just wanting to collapse.

171
00:16:19,374 --> 00:16:21,275
And you just keep, you just walk with it, that's all.

172
00:16:21,475 --> 00:16:25,741
Like you're walking with a great big fat dog that doesn't want to come with you.

173
00:16:25,761 --> 00:16:26,863
Just keep moving up and down.

174
00:16:28,565 --> 00:16:29,986
Very slowly, just very slowly.

175
00:16:30,668 --> 00:16:36,054
And then of course, don't be surprised, I'm sure some of you have experienced it, that the energy just turns.

176
00:16:36,554 --> 00:16:38,378
You know, suddenly you've got all this energy.

177
00:16:39,359 --> 00:16:39,438
Hmm?

178
00:16:40,684 --> 00:16:43,649
Sometimes it turns the other way and you find yourself being very restless.

179
00:16:43,850 --> 00:16:46,134
Then you realize they're just two sides of the same coin.

180
00:16:49,201 --> 00:17:01,243
So when it comes to something like, you know, hatred, all these delicious things that we like to enjoy, you know, cruel thoughts, getting your own back, poking people in the eye, things like that.

181
00:17:02,465 --> 00:17:02,946
Don't be...

182
00:17:03,668 --> 00:17:06,971
Be aware of that, of the self-judgment that comes with it, you know.

183
00:17:07,271 --> 00:17:09,193
How could you possibly think things like that?

184
00:17:09,213 --> 00:17:09,294
See?

185
00:17:09,734 --> 00:17:11,777
And then just note that, judging, you see.

186
00:17:11,916 --> 00:17:14,819
Remember, you can't kill the conditioning.

187
00:17:14,839 --> 00:17:16,862
You can't destroy the conditioning.

188
00:17:17,202 --> 00:17:18,864
All you can do is disempower it.

189
00:17:19,905 --> 00:17:23,710
And you disempower it by disidentifying and not joining in.

190
00:17:25,270 --> 00:17:30,537
Now, even though you may find yourself joining in unwittingly, that's not being...

191
00:17:30,887 --> 00:18:00,809
a real act of will a conscious act of will it doesn't have the force of a conscious act of will it only has the force of a conditioned will but even so it does it does push it a bit if you sat here and said to yourself I am going to murder that person see you'd be off wouldn't you you'd be writing your notes you'd be who you could phone up and see and it would be a positive line of thought driving you to murder terrible

192
00:18:01,803 --> 00:18:03,805
But here, you see, it just arises.

193
00:18:04,345 --> 00:18:06,686
You're nervous, throwing them out of the window.

194
00:18:07,147 --> 00:18:11,371
See, so when that comes up, you know, this is because you've been watching the wrong films.

195
00:18:12,913 --> 00:18:16,336
The films have taught you how to deal with these sorts of situations.

196
00:18:16,955 --> 00:18:22,020
So the mind is using all sorts of things to get rid of this problem of hating somebody.

197
00:18:22,040 --> 00:18:30,087
So when that comes up, you see, as soon as you become conscious of that dream, of that fantasy that's been created, you notice it, you see.

198
00:18:31,064 --> 00:18:32,244
You don't note the fantasy.

199
00:18:32,265 --> 00:18:35,028
You're not worried about the actual content or anything like that.

200
00:18:35,429 --> 00:18:37,490
You're worried about what's there, what's empowering it.

201
00:18:37,612 --> 00:18:38,271
So it's hatred.

202
00:18:39,594 --> 00:18:39,913
Anger.

203
00:18:40,535 --> 00:18:44,960
So then you see you come into the body and go into the body to feel.

204
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:48,064
To feel it as an emotional state.

205
00:18:48,203 --> 00:18:49,806
Because that's where the engine is.

206
00:18:50,527 --> 00:18:51,807
The engine's here in the heart.

207
00:18:52,769 --> 00:19:00,278
And so long as you keep your attention here, it has a chance of just exhausting itself.

208
00:19:01,557 --> 00:19:09,265
Every time it slips up into these higher faculties, whether you've done it wittingly or unwittingly, it is, it is turning itself, it's growing.

209
00:19:10,906 --> 00:19:20,116
I'm sure you've all had the experience of somebody saying something to you in the morning, you know, in the early part of the day at work or somewhere, and you've been slightly irritated by it.

210
00:19:21,077 --> 00:19:22,119
But you've thought nothing of it.

211
00:19:23,161 --> 00:19:28,846
And then a couple of hours later when you're having a cup of tea, you're like,

212
00:19:29,755 --> 00:19:35,582
Then come lunch, you're, and by night you've got this headache.

213
00:19:37,523 --> 00:19:39,686
And it's just because you haven't been mindful, you haven't noticed.

214
00:19:39,707 --> 00:19:49,778
Oh, as soon as the irritation arises, right, let it go, let it pass, let it just, you know, don't join in the fantasies.

215
00:19:49,798 --> 00:19:56,006
So, these emotional states generate themselves through the fantasies that they can create.

216
00:19:56,967 --> 00:19:59,289
As soon as you come off them, at least they're not generating.

217
00:19:59,557 --> 00:20:00,719
And now where can they go?

218
00:20:00,759 --> 00:20:03,182
They've got nowhere to go.

219
00:20:03,201 --> 00:20:04,924
They just have to come out through the body.

220
00:20:06,606 --> 00:20:15,239
Sometimes these things come out, sometimes they come out and they're so bedded in the body that actually they come out just as pain.

221
00:20:16,161 --> 00:20:21,087
So when you feel pain in the body, fine, it could be that the body's in the wrong posture.

222
00:20:23,131 --> 00:20:25,314
It could be the start of a terrible and dangerous illness.

223
00:20:26,315 --> 00:20:26,796
You don't know.

224
00:20:27,586 --> 00:20:35,318
But it could also be just one of these little turbulences that are blocked in the body and again all you do is just stay with it.

225
00:20:35,558 --> 00:20:36,621
Let it blow itself out.

226
00:20:37,382 --> 00:20:38,384
Just be patient with it.

227
00:20:40,287 --> 00:20:44,933
Often when it happens like that you haven't a clue what it was, what caused it.

228
00:20:44,953 --> 00:20:49,481
It's been totally dissociated from its origin.

229
00:20:52,826 --> 00:20:54,690
When it comes to the other side

230
00:20:54,873 --> 00:20:58,077
of all things that we like to indulge in.

231
00:20:58,719 --> 00:21:03,445
You know, the lusts and the greeds, making money, fame.

232
00:21:05,269 --> 00:21:07,172
When will my 15 minutes of fame come?

233
00:21:09,634 --> 00:21:15,243
As soon as the mind begins to agitate around that, well, these are quite delicious things to get into, you see.

234
00:21:15,832 --> 00:21:20,137
So here you have to really be quite sharp and quite disciplined.

235
00:21:20,778 --> 00:21:34,916
And as you come away from it, you see, as you come away from that thought pattern and you come into the body to feel whatever the emotion is, the excited emotion is that's empowering it, you see, you see, you have to make a determination not to go there.

236
00:21:36,077 --> 00:21:42,125
Now, if you come into the body to feel this but there's still a part of you that wants to go to that fantasy,

237
00:21:42,663 --> 00:21:46,268
You see, it only takes a moment of mindfulness and off you go.

238
00:21:46,307 --> 00:21:50,432
Half an hour later, you think, oh God, come back.

239
00:21:51,614 --> 00:21:54,999
So you have to stop, you see, you have to stop and say, you have to acknowledge it, you see.

240
00:21:55,538 --> 00:21:58,762
Ah, planning, planning, you know, planning the next great move.

241
00:21:59,564 --> 00:22:04,431
See, and then as you come off it, you can still feel that desire to go there.

242
00:22:05,050 --> 00:22:07,994
You have to stay with that desire, wait for it to begin to decrease.

243
00:22:10,777 --> 00:22:14,320
You have to be patient with that because sometimes they're very strong.

244
00:22:18,026 --> 00:22:22,711
When it comes to restlessness, again, don't fight it.

245
00:22:23,932 --> 00:22:26,276
It's much more to do with sort of relaxing around it.

246
00:22:26,536 --> 00:22:34,806
If it's a restlessness in the body, just relax what you can of the body around that feeling of wanting to get up, wanting to move.

247
00:22:36,167 --> 00:22:38,049
Whatever it appears in your hands,

248
00:22:40,509 --> 00:22:42,991
Just relax around it.

249
00:22:43,313 --> 00:22:43,833
Just relax.

250
00:22:45,194 --> 00:22:49,858
And then put your attention right into those feelings of that restlessness.

251
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:51,780
And just stay there.

252
00:22:51,901 --> 00:22:52,701
Investigate that.

253
00:22:52,741 --> 00:22:53,623
Feel that.

254
00:22:54,903 --> 00:22:58,268
See it more just as little transient moments of sensations.

255
00:23:00,609 --> 00:23:07,497
Remember that the mind is always picking up a set of sensations and creating something out of it.

256
00:23:09,738 --> 00:23:36,758
it creates objects in the world for us which is necessary you don't live in the world not being able to see objects but we keep being fooled by it that's the problem so when you go when you feel restless you see this is one of those sensations that you can really get into and see that all it is is just little moments of these fiery fiery movements fiery windy movements

257
00:23:39,521 --> 00:23:42,689
The mind is more difficult when it's really restless.

258
00:23:43,329 --> 00:23:44,471
Some people think they're going mad.

259
00:23:45,674 --> 00:23:46,395
But we are mad.

260
00:23:47,137 --> 00:23:50,243
There shouldn't be any worries about going mad.

261
00:23:50,263 --> 00:23:51,326
It's pretty straightforward.

262
00:23:51,826 --> 00:23:53,109
Everybody's mad.

263
00:23:53,130 --> 00:23:57,538
Only somebody who's fully awakened is not mad.

264
00:24:00,084 --> 00:24:00,905
There's very few of us.

265
00:24:01,932 --> 00:24:11,365
So when the mind goes berserk and it just won't stop thinking no matter what you do, it really is just so empowered and it's just going berserk inside there, you see.

266
00:24:11,384 --> 00:24:13,126
So just be patient, see.

267
00:24:13,146 --> 00:24:17,112
Okay, so now that's all firing away on all pistons, you see.

268
00:24:17,132 --> 00:24:20,416
So very gently you shoot off and you just come back.

269
00:24:20,616 --> 00:24:22,419
Just be patient with it, be patient with it.

270
00:24:23,059 --> 00:24:31,872
The important thing is not to make an act of will, a conscious act of will to indulge what the mind is telling you to do.

271
00:24:32,762 --> 00:24:33,763
That's the crucial thing.

272
00:24:36,106 --> 00:24:43,454
And you can sort of do a half-conscious will where there's a part of you saying, no, no, just watch, just watch.

273
00:24:43,474 --> 00:24:46,939
And the other part is saying, just have a peep, just have a peep.

274
00:24:47,358 --> 00:24:51,324
And before you know it, whoop!

275
00:24:51,344 --> 00:24:54,547
And then of course it goes really buggered.

276
00:24:54,567 --> 00:24:59,512
So make a clear, you see, these moments of reflection

277
00:25:00,859 --> 00:25:06,586
In your sitting, it's very skillful to stop every thought and just ask yourself what you're doing.

278
00:25:07,989 --> 00:25:09,490
You know, like, what am I doing now?

279
00:25:09,590 --> 00:25:10,853
Why am I going berserk, you see?

280
00:25:12,535 --> 00:25:17,280
These little moments of reflection and ask yourself, am I using, what techniques have I been taught?

281
00:25:17,781 --> 00:25:20,224
In what ways can I handle this particular problem?

282
00:25:21,326 --> 00:25:26,893
There's nothing wrong with thinking about your, reflecting and thinking about your meditation as you're sitting.

283
00:25:27,093 --> 00:25:28,335
That's what you're supposed to be doing.

284
00:25:28,737 --> 00:25:30,759
If you lose it, you're supposed to save yourself.

285
00:25:30,778 --> 00:25:31,599
What's going wrong here?

286
00:25:39,789 --> 00:25:49,301
Doubt, self-doubt, you know, doubting whether you can do it or whether you should be doing it or is this the right time to do it and all that sort of stuff.

287
00:25:49,321 --> 00:25:53,446
So, doubt is just, where's it coming from, doubt?

288
00:25:53,666 --> 00:25:55,348
Where's the base of doubt, you see?

289
00:25:56,390 --> 00:25:57,731
It comes from don't know, doesn't it?

290
00:25:58,234 --> 00:26:01,218
If you know, if you know, there's no doubt, is there?

291
00:26:01,817 --> 00:26:07,442
I mean, if you know that lunch is at 12.15 and you've seen it written here, then there's no doubt.

292
00:26:08,364 --> 00:26:13,528
It's only if you haven't seen it or somebody said maybe it's at 12.15 that you've got this doubt.

293
00:26:13,909 --> 00:26:16,491
So then you run around the place asking everybody, when's lunch?

294
00:26:16,511 --> 00:26:17,353
When's lunch?

295
00:26:17,373 --> 00:26:19,555
We're going to miss lunch.

296
00:26:19,894 --> 00:26:22,738
That sort of sense of doubt comes from this business of not knowing.

297
00:26:22,778 --> 00:26:25,440
It's a place where we really don't like to be.

298
00:26:26,432 --> 00:26:28,255
You know, the self likes to know.

299
00:26:28,275 --> 00:26:29,797
It likes to be able to control.

300
00:26:29,936 --> 00:26:31,499
It likes to know what's going to happen tomorrow.

301
00:26:32,441 --> 00:26:33,442
It's got it all planned out.

302
00:26:33,561 --> 00:26:36,405
And when I retire, all that sort of stuff.

303
00:26:36,425 --> 00:26:36,645
You see?

304
00:26:37,026 --> 00:26:43,755
So this business of staying in the don't know, of staying at a place where you are afraid, see?

305
00:26:43,894 --> 00:26:45,096
Where there's anxiety.

306
00:26:46,298 --> 00:26:50,143
And not to let it shake you into don't know.

307
00:26:50,202 --> 00:26:53,307
And then suddenly, I don't know whether I can, whether I should.

308
00:26:54,327 --> 00:26:55,108
Should I, shouldn't I?

309
00:26:55,549 --> 00:26:55,630
See?

310
00:26:56,368 --> 00:27:23,692
Now, when the mind gets locked into those doubts about what you should be doing, whether you should be sitting or not sitting, whether you should be here or not here, in moments of life, whether you should be taking this job or not that job, whether you should be going into a relationship or not a relationship, you know, and all those points where doubt comes up, you see, don't get lost so much in the mentation, but rest with that feeling of anxiety and fear that comes up when you don't know.

311
00:27:24,382 --> 00:27:34,951
And just let time, let more information come in before you rush into some sort of decision.

312
00:27:37,835 --> 00:27:43,960
So here, when you're meditating, you see, and the mind goes berserk and all that, you can hear it sometimes, you know.

313
00:27:43,980 --> 00:27:45,582
Oh, you can't do this, you're wasting your time.

314
00:27:47,483 --> 00:27:48,884
There's the doubt, see.

315
00:27:49,685 --> 00:27:51,768
Normally we say, yeah, it's true, right, let's get up and go.

316
00:27:53,528 --> 00:27:54,269
You're fed up with this.

317
00:27:54,570 --> 00:28:24,544
so be careful about doubt it's very tricky it's something that we very quickly get into because it's so it's such a relief from having to feel the anxiety that's beneath it it's much easier to run around like a chicken than it is to sit there with the feelings of fear and anxiety around the decision you know lists A and B for and against should I, shouldn't I

318
00:28:25,282 --> 00:28:30,308
And it's often a case of just staying there with those feelings of anxiety around doubt.

319
00:28:33,211 --> 00:28:36,255
In the spiritual practice, of course, it's really pernicious.

320
00:28:36,295 --> 00:28:41,121
Well, it's pernicious in all forms of life to have sceptical doubt because it stops you doing, it stops you committing.

321
00:28:43,683 --> 00:28:48,710
So at some point you have to say yes and you have to, as it were, jump and hope for the best.

322
00:28:50,811 --> 00:28:55,257
And we can't do that if you see life in terms of success and failure.

323
00:28:56,214 --> 00:28:58,438
It's not nice to do something if you think you're going to fail.

324
00:28:59,538 --> 00:29:06,709
But if you see life more as an investigation, more as a trial and error, then you lose that fear of failure.

325
00:29:07,209 --> 00:29:16,121
So that takes away a lot of that fear of making a decision and thinking you're going to make a prat of yourself.

326
00:29:16,141 --> 00:29:17,442
Other people can think you're a prat.

327
00:29:18,243 --> 00:29:19,404
That doesn't matter.

328
00:29:20,109 --> 00:29:20,990
It shouldn't matter.

329
00:29:21,571 --> 00:29:28,159
It should be up to us and ourselves as to why we've done something for a specific purpose.

330
00:29:28,179 --> 00:29:34,926
So, when it comes to doubt, get on it quickly, especially in your meditation.

331
00:29:36,169 --> 00:29:37,029
It's a crippling thing.

332
00:29:39,112 --> 00:29:42,316
I think I've covered most of them, I think.

333
00:29:42,336 --> 00:29:49,324
Doubt, guilt, restless, sleepiness, all those things we love, all those things we hate,

334
00:29:51,211 --> 00:29:55,038
And what we're trying to do is to become skillful.

335
00:29:56,420 --> 00:30:00,647
And if we can be skillful with it in the sitting, we should be able to take it out into daily life.

336
00:30:02,811 --> 00:30:10,705
So that this differentiation we make between sitting and daily life, they should fade into each other.

337
00:30:10,726 --> 00:30:14,973
There shouldn't be any distinction.

338
00:30:27,221 --> 00:30:33,613
So, from now to lunchtime, it's up to you really what you want to do.

339
00:30:33,893 --> 00:30:35,174
A bit of walking, a bit of sitting.

340
00:30:35,976 --> 00:30:36,817
Keep your own time.

341
00:30:39,182 --> 00:30:41,546
Lunchtime is a bit more formal.

342
00:30:42,166 --> 00:30:47,255
I'll be offered food and then I'll wait for you all to eat.

343
00:30:47,736 --> 00:30:49,218
Sorry, to be served.

344
00:30:49,679 --> 00:30:50,500
Or to serve yourself.

345
00:30:51,382 --> 00:30:52,182
And then I'll...

346
00:30:53,142 --> 00:30:58,227
And then I'll do a little chant just to make it a bit more formal.

347
00:30:59,347 --> 00:30:59,989
And then we can eat.

348
00:31:00,669 --> 00:31:06,095
And remember, the eating is part of our investigation.

349
00:31:06,115 --> 00:31:07,476
The whole process of pleasure.

350
00:31:09,038 --> 00:31:14,962
If we can understand how to enjoy food, which is so basic, we have to do it every day.

351
00:31:15,943 --> 00:31:18,626
It's so great to have to be with that in a non-indulgent way.

352
00:31:19,483 --> 00:31:24,131
And we should be able to translate that into all the pleasures of our life.

353
00:31:28,337 --> 00:31:36,069
When the Buddha described what it was like to be in a state of Nibbana, he said he was contented and with it happy.

354
00:31:38,413 --> 00:31:40,416
How bad is it?

355
00:31:40,436 --> 00:31:42,259
Contented and with it happy.

356
00:31:45,806 --> 00:31:47,127
So with those encouraging words,

357
00:31:49,403 --> 00:31:51,269
So take advantage of your time, you know.

358
00:31:52,112 --> 00:31:59,498
And as I say, today is just being with yourself, letting things burn off.

